    The problem description explicitly states: "The initialization loop on      
    line 176 uses 'v_count' (variable count) as the upper bound instead of      
    'a_count' (array count). When v_count > a_count, the loop writes past the   
    allocated a_names/arrays heap buffers, corrupting heap metadata and         
    causing a crash in subsequent lookups."                                     
                                                                                
    My get_code_surrounding for bc/storage.c:176 and bc/storage.c:170           
    confirmed:                                                                  
                                                                                
     • Line 176: for (; indx < v_count; indx++) iterates using v_count.         
     • Line 166: a_count += STORE_INCR; and lines 167-168 show a_count is used  
       for allocation: arrays = (bc_var_array **) bc_malloc                     
       (a_count*sizeof(bc_var_array *)); and a_names = (char **) bc_malloc      
       (a_count*sizeof(char *));.                                               
                                                                                
    This confirms the issue is exactly as described. a_count represents the     
    allocated size, and v_count can exceed it, leading to a heap buffer         
    overflow when writing to arrays[indx] in the loop on line 176.              
                                                                                
    ROOT CAUSE: bc/storage.c:176. The loop intended to initialize newly         
    allocated array elements arrays at line 176 for (; indx < v_count; indx++)  
    uses v_count as its upper bound. However, the arrays arrays and a_names     
    were allocated using a_count as the size at lines 167 and 168. If v_count   
    happens to be greater than a_count (which can happen if v_count was         
    already close to a_count before a_count was incremented by STORE_INCR),     
    the loop will write beyond the bounds of the allocated memory for arrays,   
    causing a heap buffer overflow.                                             
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX:                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
