     @@ -173,7 +173,7 @@                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
        /* Initialize the new elements. */                                      
     -  for (; indx < v_count; indx++)                                          
     +  for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                          
          arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                  
                                                                                
        /* Free the old elements. */                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this class of bug where an allocation size is        
    mismatched with a loop bound, a more robust solution would be to            
    encapsulate the array and its size within a structure, or use a custom      
    container class that manages its own capacity and size. This way, all       
    operations on the array (allocation, access, iteration) would consistently  
    refer to the same size field. In C, a common pattern for this is to keep    
    the size alongside the pointer, for example by defining a struct Array {    
    void** data; size_t capacity; size_t count; }; and passing this structure   
    around, ensuring capacity is always used for allocation and bounds          
    checking, while count is used for logical element count. In this specific   
    case, bc_var_array could be extended to include its size, or a helper       
    function could be used to reallocate and initialize the arrays that takes   
    the array and its actual capacity.                                          
